subsection.p:
If E is an oriented solid with outward boundary \partial E, then

  \boxed{
  \int_{\partial E}\Phi_{\mathbf F}
  =
  \int_E d\Phi_{\mathbf F}.
  }

Since

  d\Phi_{\mathbf F}
  =
  (P_x+Q_y+R_z)\,dx\wedge dy\wedge dz,

this becomes

  \boxed{
  \int_{\partial E}\Phi_{\mathbf F}
  =
  \iiint_E
  (P_x+Q_y+R_z)\,dx\wedge dy\wedge dz.
  }

p.md:
\begin{array}{ll}
1. \amp E\text{ is a bounded solid with piecewise smooth boundary.}\\
2. \amp \partial E\text{ is oriented outward.}\\
3. \amp \mathbf F\text{ has continuous first partial derivatives on a region containing }E.
\end{array}

\begin{array}{ll}
1. \amp \text{Flux forms.}\\
2. \amp \text{Exterior derivative of a }2\text{-form.}\\
3. \amp \text{Triple integrals.}\\
4. \amp \text{Cancellation across shared faces.}\\
5. \amp \text{Single-variable FTC along coordinate directions.}
\end{array}
